</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org3c81750" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org3c81750">Directory Indexing</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org3c81750">
<p>
Directory indexing is when a web-sever list the contents of a directory on a web-server path. The information show can give the attacker good info on whats installed and what he can abuse.
Checking for indexing is just you going to a folder and seeing if you get a dir listing.
Dirs to check:
</p>
<pre class="example" id="org66d0622">
/wp-content/
/wp-content/plugins/
/wp-content/themes/
/uploads/
/images/
</pre>
</div>
</div>


<div id="outline-container-org13af7ed" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org13af7ed">Tools</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org13af7ed">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org380e351" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org380e351">WPScan</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-org380e351">
<p>
WPScan is a common WordPress security tool that ties these methods, allow you to quickly enumerate a WordPress install. it has a commercial license that restricts the use for personal testing.
</p>

<p>
Link: <a href="https://github.com/wpscanteam/wpscan">https://github.com/wpscanteam/wpscan</a>
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org777f323" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org777f323">Nmap</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-org777f323">
<p>
Nmap comes with NSE scripts that allow the scanner to do more
scripts helpful for WordPress
</p>
<pre class="example" id="orgc35ed80">
http-WordPress-brute.nse
http-wordpress-enum.nse
http-wordpress-users.nse
</pre>
